To demonstrate XCT in the SXR range, an experiment in the water window using synchrotron radiation has been performed. A layered sample consisting of a 8 nm platinum layer buried under a boron carbide layer has been produced and investigated by XCT. It is depicted in Fig. 3a. The measured reflectivity captured by swept-source XCT is shown in Fig. 3b. The blue line represents the interpolation of measurements acquired for different monochromator positions. In analogy to the previous data in the silicon window, the spectrum is multiplied by a filter function (dashed line). The XCT signal (c, dot–dashed curve) shows three distinct peaks. The peaks at 17 nm and 25 nm represent the position of the frontside and backside of the platinum layer, respectively. The peak at 7.7 nm is the autocorrelation artifact representing the difference in depth of the frontside and backside of the platinum layer. With the PR-XCT, it is possible to eliminate the ghost artifacts and reconstruct the real sample reflectivity. Note that in contrast to the silicon-window measurement, the amplitude of the peak at ζ=0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\zeta =0\,$$\end{document}nm is much higher due to the higher reflectivity of the platinum capping layer. The axial resolution is defined by the bandwidth and the filter function and is as high as 7 nm (FWHM). The two layers with a distance of 8 nm are clearly separated demonstrating XCT can achieve single-digit nanometer axial resolution.

